## PHASE 3 — Domain-Specific Friction Reports

### 3.1 Low-Level Hackers / Systems
*Strengths:* `i8/i16/i32/i64/u*/f32/f64`, `%T` pointer types, `%`/`@` ref/deref, `volatile_load/store`, `wrapping_*`/`saturating_*`/`checked_*`, `signal_*`, `@packed`/`@strict`/`@align(N)` layout decorators. SSO strings & contiguous structs.
*Frictions:*
- `asm` is in lexer but no documented inline-asm form; verifying execution would require dedicated tests.
- No `unsafe` block — repo notes brand this "sharp" philosophy. For systems work, that means **there is no syntactic marker** for memory-aggressive code, which makes audit harder rather than easier.
- No control over calling convention, no `#[link_section]`, no `#[no_mangle]` per-function (only crude `--lib`).
- No way to take address of a function value with a stable ABI signature for plugging into a C callback table without going through `extern`.
- No `__builtin_*` exposure; missed-opportunity for SIMD intrinsics (SIMD was explicitly removed per memory).
- Cross-compilation effectively absent (F-BE-3).

### 3.2 Data Science / Math / Science
- `dataframe.jade`, `stats.jade`, `fft.jade`, `complex.jade`, `decimal.jade`, `rational.jade`, `bigint.jade` exist on paper.
- **No SIMD**, **no `matmul`/`einsum`/`grad`** (explicitly removed per memory). For numerical-Python replacement claims, this is fatal.
- No tensor type. `dataframe.jade` is a Jade-level wrapper, almost certainly without columnar storage given runtime/`column.c` is only 275 lines.
- **No REPL.** A command-line `jadec` only compiles whole programs; jupyter-class iteration is impossible.
- Numeric precision is fine (i8…i64, f32/f64) but no `f16`/`bf16`/`f128`.

### 3.3 Web Backend / DevOps
- `http.jade`, `net.jade`, `tls.jade` exist.
- No async/await keywords; concurrency is via actors/spawn. Suitable but unfamiliar to the typical web developer.
- No router, no middleware story, no JSON deserialization to typed structs verified in std (json.jade exists but typed-bind story unclear).
- **No hot-code reloading** — runtime has no module-replacement protocol.
- Persistence story (Phase 2.6) means hosting actual production state on Jade stores is **not advisable**; web backends will end up calling out to `sqlite.jade` (a wrapper), defeating the "no DB layer" claim.
- Container footprint should be small (no GC, single static binary), but `cc`-shellout linker dependency means CI base images need a C toolchain present.

