## Bottom-line scoring (panel consensus)

| Subsystem | Grade | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| Lexer / Parser | **B-** | Solid hand-written; single-error abort and reserved-keyword cruft hurt. |
| Type Inference | **B** | Real Union-Find HM with bidir + constraints; soundness eroded by silent fallbacks; not "complete" as promised. |
| HIR / MIR / Perceus | **C+** | Capable, but architecturally fragmented (dual IRs, dual Perceus, dual codegens). |
| LLVM Codegen | **B** | Modular, correct IR, decent SSO/dyn-trait; debug info weak; cross-compile absent. |
| Runtime (sched/coro/channel) | **A−** | The crown jewel: real M:N scheduler with work-stealing, hand-rolled coroutines, robust channels. Underrated. |
| Actors (as a feature) | **C** | Sugar over channels; no supervision, no selective receive, no isolation. Promise unmet. |
| Persistence (stores+WAL) | **D** | Marketing/code mismatch; no fsync, no real ACID, fixed 256 B slots, linear scans. |
| Stdlib | **C** | Surface-broad, depth unverified; several stubs documented in repo memory. |
| Tooling / Docs | **C-** | LSP and tree-sitter exist; main doc starts with a corrupted line; `jadec` lacks REPL/cross-compile. |
| Performance | **A−** | 1.04× C geomean (5-bench) is a serious accomplishment for a young language. |

**Aggregate alpha-readiness:** the **runtime and inference engine are publishable**; the **type-soundness escape hatches, persistence claims, and dual-IR compiler architecture are blockers** for an honest 0.x → α transition. The roadmap above (P0-1 through P0-5) is the minimum bar.

