## What is actually true (Phase 1: facts in evidence)

### Compiler architecture (verified)
- **Single MIR-based pipeline.** `Lexer → Parser → AST → Typer → HIR → MIR(lower) → MIR(opt) → MIR(perceus) → MirCodegen → LLVM` (main.rs).
- **HIR codegen modules are utility code** for the MIR codegen: type lowering, RC, drops, store-runtime decls. They expose `compile_expr`, `compile_store_insert`, etc. that the MIR codegen calls in narrow situations (default-field initializers, store ops still routed through the older HIR helper).
- **Two Perceus implementations exist.** perceus (HIR-side) and mir_perceus.rs. Both ran on every program I compiled — the build output prints `perceus: ...` *and* `mir-perceus: ...` lines on every compile. So the HIR Perceus produces hints for the HIR helpers, and MIR Perceus produces hints for the MIR-native paths. This duplication remains and is the residual cost of the pipeline merger.

### Type system (verified)
- Real Union-Find HM with bidirectional checking, post-pass `resolve_all_types`, constraint kinds (`Numeric/Addable/Integer/Float/Trait`), trait-impl checking, occurs check (unify.rs).
- **Implicit polymorphism works at top level.** `*identity x; *compose f, g; *twice f, x` compiled and ran — one compile produced `42`, `'hello'`, `3.14`, `22`, `7` (verified output). So your "T2" claim — principal-type discovery for top-level functions — is empirically supported.
- **Defaulting warnings are emitted, not silenced.** `poly2.jade` produced `warning: line 10:13: unsolved type variable defaulted to i64 (function argument). Consider adding ': i64' or the appropriate type annotation.` That is a properly attributed defaulting warning with a fix-suggestion — this was overlooked in my last pass.
- **Real type errors are reported with provenance.** `types_break.jade` (`y is x + 5` where `x is 'hello'`) reports `hir-validate: BinOp Add type mismatch at line 3: lhs String vs rhs I64`. The location is correct.

### Concurrency runtime (verified)
- sched.c is a **real M:N work-stealing scheduler**: per-worker Chase-Lev deques (deque.c), global inject queue protected by an MCS-flavoured spinlock with x86 `pause` / aarch64 `yield` (sched.c), two-phase parking (40-spin + cond_timedwait at 100 µs, sched.c), worker count `min(NCPU, 8)` (sched.c).
- Hand-rolled context switch in context_x86_64.S and context_aarch64.S.
- This is materially better than I credited it last round.

### Persistence (verified, partly worse than I said, partly better)
- Better: indexed lookups exist via `jade_idx_*` functions in index.c (open-addressed hash with linear probing, FNV-1a, automatic 2× growth at load 0.7). The MIR store codegen actually calls them (store.rs,store.rs,store.rs).
- KV store (kv.c) is in-memory hash + on-disk persistence, fixed 256 B keys.
- Worse-than-I-said: **WAL has no `fsync` or `fdatasync` anywhere.** I grepped all of `runtime/*.c` for `fsync|fdatasync|msync|O_SYNC|O_DSYNC` and got zero hits. wal.c only calls `fflush` ([wal.c L61, L111, L124](runtime/wal.c#L61)). After `fflush`, data sits in the kernel page cache; a power loss before writeback loses committed records. The "WAL" name overpromises what is currently implemented.
- Field record format still uses **fixed 256 B string slots** (stores.rs `STRING_BUF_SIZE = 256`). I verified empirically: my `users.store` was 4,872 bytes for 6 records of `(name as String, age as i64)` — ~812 B/record — confirming the layout. This is fine for short uniform schemas, brutal for variable-length data.

### Standard library (corrected)
- 40 modules, ~7,245 LOC. **Zero `TODO`/`FIXME`/`stub`/`unimplemented`/`placeholder` markers** in any `.jade` file. I verified `head -40 std/json.jade` and `head -40 std/http.jade`: both are substantive implementations (a 445-line typed JSON, a 290-line HTTP/1.1 client with URL parser). My previous "depth unverified, several stubs" was lazy.

